SIMPLE: metalloid
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Metalloid
<hw>Met"al*loid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>metallum</ets> metal + <ets>-oid</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧tallo⟦ium⟧de</ets>.]</ety> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Formerly, the
metallic base of a fixed alkali, or alkaline earth; -- applied by
<person>Sir Humphrey Davy</person> to sodium, potassium, and some other
metallic substances whose metallic character was supposed to be not well
defined.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Now, one of several elementary
substances which in the free state are unlike metals, and whose
compounds possess or produce acid, rather than basic, properties; a
nonmetal; <as>as, boron, carbon, phosphorus, nitrogen, oxygen, sulphur,
chlorine, bromine, etc.</as>, are <xex>metalloids</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalloid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Metalloid
<hw>Met"al*loid</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the
appearance of a metal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Having the properties of a
nonmetal; nonmetallic; acid; negative.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalloidal</ent>⟦br⟧
